### EXAMPLE 3: UNCHECKED_LOW_LEVEL_CALLS VULNERABILITY

**Vulnerable Code:**
```solidity
contract generic_holder {
    address owner;

    modifier onlyowner {
        if (owner == msg.sender)
            _;
    }

    // constructor
    function generic_holder() {
        owner = msg.sender;
    }

    function change_owner(address new_owner) external onlyowner {
        owner = new_owner;
    }

    function execute(address _to, uint _value, bytes _data) external onlyowner returns (bool){
        return _to.call.value(_value)(_data);
    }

    function get_owner() constant returns (address) {
        return owner;
    }
}
```

**Security Analysis:**
This code contains a unchecked_low_level_calls vulnerability.

Yes — the original analysis was on-point, but here’s a tighter, self-contained write-up:

1. Vulnerable pattern  
   • In your execute() you do something like  
     return _to.call.value(_value)(_data);  
   • That is a raw low-level call. In Solidity .call never bubbles up a revert — it simply returns false on any failure (out-of-gas, revert in the target, invalid opcode, etc.).  
   • You don’t check that false. You hand it straight back to the caller as if it were a normal return.  

2. Why unchecked low-level calls are unsafe  
   • The caller (e.g. the contract owner) thinks “I transferred ETH or invoked the external logic.”  
   • If the target’s fallback or function reverts or runs out of gas, .call returns false and swallows the failure.  
   • Because there is no require or if(success) guard, neither the caller nor your contract ever sees the failure. Subsequent logic proceeds under a false assumption of success.  

3. Attack or failure scenarios  
   • Even though only the owner can invoke execute(), they may be calling a third-party DeFi contract, token contract, auction, etc.  
   • If that external contract’s code reverts for any reason — bad input, internal require, gas exhaustion — the low-level call fails silently.  
   • The owner and your contract think the funds went through or the action completed, but in fact it didn’t. This can lock funds, corrupt state, break invariants, or lead to cascading failures elsewhere.  

4. Conditions for exploitation  
   • The contract uses address.call(...) without immediately checking its boolean return value.  
   • The caller relies on execute() to convey success or failure.  
   • The target contract can be made to revert or run out of gas.  

5. The simple fix  
   • Always capture and guard the return value:  
     bool success = _to.call.value(_value)(_data);  
     require(success, “External call failed”);  
   • This way any failure in the external call bubbles up and reverts your contract, keeping state consistent.


**Classification**: This code contains a **unchecked_low_level_calls** vulnerability.

