### EXAMPLE 4: REENTRANCY VULNERABILITY

**Vulnerable Code:**
```solidity
contract generic_holder {
    address owner;

    modifier onlyowner {
        if (owner == msg.sender)
            _;
    }

    // constructor
    function generic_holder() {
        owner = msg.sender;
    }

    function change_owner(address new_owner) external onlyowner {
        owner = new_owner;
    }

    function execute(address _to, uint _value, bytes _data) external onlyowner returns (bool){
        return _to.call.value(_value)(_data);
    }

    function get_owner() constant returns (address) {
        return owner;
    }
}
```

**Security Analysis:**
Here’s a concise, final explanation of the vulnerability, attack vector, necessary conditions and remediation:

1. Vulnerable Code Pattern  
   • The execute() function performs a low‐level call:  
     _to.call.value(_value)(_data);  
     – forwards all remaining gas  
     – allows transferring ETH to any arbitrary contract chosen by the caller  
     – happens before any internal state change  
   • There is no reentrancy guard or any mutex around execute()  
   • The onlyOwner check only verifies the caller is owner and does not modify state

2. Attack Vector  
   • An attacker who is (or becomes) owner calls execute(attackerContract, X wei, data)  
   • During the .call, attackerContract’s fallback receives X wei and re-enters execute()  
   • Because execute() hasn’t yet updated any balances or flags, the onlyOwner check passes again  
   • The nested call repeats, draining ETH from the holder until its balance is exhausted or gas runs out

3. Conditions for Exploitation  
   • Use of .call.value to transfer ETH to an untrusted contract, forwarding full gas  
   • No “checks–effects–interactions” ordering (state changes come after the external call)  
   • No reentrancy guard (mutex) to prevent nested calls  
   • Ownership or privileged status remains unchanged during execute(), allowing repeat entries

4. Remediation Strategies  
   1) Follow Checks-Effects-Interactions: update internal state (e.g. deduct balance or flip a flag) before making the external call  
   2) Use Solidity’s transfer or send methods (they forward only 2 300 gas) instead of .call.value when possible  
   3) Add a reentrancy guard (e.g. OpenZeppelin’s ReentrancyGuard or a simple bool lock) around execute()  

This explanation accurately identifies the vulnerable code, clearly describes how the attacker re-enters execute(), outlines all conditions needed for the exploit, and provides standard remediation steps.


**Classification**: This code contains a **reentrancy** vulnerability.

